rs the emergence of a larger trend of history writing by unusual authors-people outside the learned establishment-and a new phenomenon: nouveau literacy. The Barber of Damascus offers the first full-length microhistory of an individual commoner in Ottoman and Islamic history. Contributing to Ottoman popular history, Arabic historiography, and the little-studied cultural history of the 18th century Levant, the volume also examines the reception of the barber's book a century later to explore connections between the 18th and the late 19th centuries and illuminates new paths leading to the Nahda, the Arab Renaissance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aArabic prose literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aBarberszSyriazDamascusvBiography. 0aLiterature and societyzMiddle EastxHistoryy18th century. 4aBarber. 4aDamascus. 4aMuḥammad Sa`īd al-Qāsimī. 4aShihāb al-Dīn Aḥmad Ibn Budayr. 4aal-Nahḍa (Arab Renaissance). 4acontemporary chronicle. 4amicrohistory. 4anouveau literacy. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804788281zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804788281423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804788281.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles